---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "rollercoaster";
const subtitle = "new web";
const bannerImage =
    "https://64.media.tumblr.com/93e8bf7ab2241196d8c5e50adf428472/47da191381c73af5-71/s500x750/272686bc418052e11c14eed5bc029161563a409b.gifv";
const tinyImage = "/smalls/computer6.gif";
---

<Layout
    title={title}
    subtitle={subtitle}
    bannerImage={bannerImage}
    tinyImage={tinyImage}
>
    <div slot="main-text">
        <p>
            i hadn't heard much about the new web movement until one day i got
            on the right side of youtube and watched a <a
                href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yko-LMBrRQw&t=11s"
                >LuvstarKei IRL</a
            > video. I remember building cool pages like this before - my Tumblr account,
            my sister's Tumblr account...another Tumblr account. Point being I learned
            how to change the background image and felt like a bonafied hacker.
        </p>
        <br />
        <div class="center">
            <iframe
                src="https://giphy.com/embed/JIX9t2j0ZTN9S"
                width="200"
                height="200"
                style=""
                class="giphy-embed"></iframe>
        </div>
        <br />
        <p>
            this inspired me to get back to the thing i love most - building my
            own little world. here we can arrange pixels and categorize topics
            by whatever limitations our brains and html can go towards. I was
            ready to make this website before I even could think of a reason to
            create one in the first place. I am all style with just a dash of
            substance here. So I supposed in exchange for having a place to
            share all these cool carousel horse pngs I found... I could bother
            to impart some wisdom.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div slot="full">
        <h2>why make a site?</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <mark>Freedom</mark> - you get to post whatever you want, no algo,
                no content guidelines, no text limit, and no format restrictions
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>skill building</mark> - i'm putting css and html on my resume
                as we speak.
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>nostalgia</mark> - so many of the resouces out there pay homage
                to old web, it's hilarious watching young zoomers posting "rawrxd"
                blinkies in their profiles
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>fuck capitalism</mark> - decentralize the web. stop algorithms
                for making choices for you. explore and currate your own web experience.
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>community</mark> - I've been able to meet new urls and profile
                pictures all thanks to the small web. It's making media social again!
            </li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div slot="left-half">
        <h2>so you're ready to start working on your own site?</h2>

        <p>
            <b>lets goooo!!!</b> Sadly i can't teach you how to code...or build a
            website. But i can teach you how <i>i</i> learned to do it. and if this
            clown with a journalism degree can figure this out I'm sure you can too!
        </p>

        <ol>
            <li>
                <mark>explore the sites</mark>: check out my <a
                    href="/me/shuttle.html">shuttle bus</a
                > to other pages and see what they've created. get inspired and know
                what you want to make
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>get a template</mark>: the scary open notepad was very
                intimidating at first, but editing a template was the training
                wheels i needed to learn my divs from my ps
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>set up your work area</mark>: You'll need a few things to
                get started. You'll need a place to write, edit, and preview
                your code. Most people use <a
                    href="https://code.visualstudio.com/download?_exp_download=fb315fc982"
                    >VS code</a
                > - including me!
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>eat sleep and breathe tutorials</mark> i still find myself googling
                " how to make image centered", if you have seen it online it can be
                done. learn the terminology you need and eventually you will figure
                it out. it's like a puzzle
            </li>
            <li>
                <mark>you will make errors, accept it</mark> fellow perfectionists
                read this and go "okay but like I'll do my best not to make them..."
                <b> stop yourself right now</b>. Stop trying to find the perfect
                html tutorial and just start something. if your errors are
                deadly you'll trouble shoot. If your layout looks crooked,
                you'll learn how to center. You will learn best by throwing some
                mud on the canvas and figuring everything out as you go along.
                Personal websites are made for learning.
            </li>
        </ol>
        <div class="center">
            <iframe
                width="187"
                height="105"
                src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/p4l5PpdvNGY?si=IqWOx-ihqykqF9V6"
                title="YouTube video player"
                frameborder="0"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
                allowfullscreen></iframe>
        </div>
        <div class="center">
            <i
                >this is the tutorial i followed and it helped me crawl my way
                through my first build!</i
            >
        </div>
        <h3>resources</h3>
        <div class="flexbox">
            <a href="https://sadgrlonline.github.io/archived-sadgrl.online/"
                ><img
                    src="https://sadgrlonline.github.io/archived-sadgrl.online/assets/images/buttons/sadgrlonline.gif"
                /></a
            >
            <a
                href="https://luvstarkei.com/website-resources-and-graphics-collection/"
                ><img src="/link-backs/LuvstarKeiButton-1.webp" /></a
            >
            <a href="https://32bit.cafe/"
                ><img src="https://32bit.cafe/linktous/32b-pcb.png" /></a
            >
            <a href="https://petrapixel.neocities.org/" target="_blank"
                ><img
                    src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/petracoding/petrapixel.neocities.org@latest/public/assets/img/linkback.gif"
                    alt="petrapixel"
                /></a
            >
            <h3>Helpful Links</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/">W3 Schools</a> Very easy
                    to follow beginner HTML tutorial
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://astro.build/">Astro</a> A javascript web framework
                    (aka make it easier to repeat content like layouts)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/">VS Studio Code</a> Open
                    source coder (ai functions can be turned off)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a
                        href="https://scumsuck.com/resources/deployneocities/#before-you-start-3"
                        >Deploying to Neocities</a
                    > I did not understand the first thing about github until i read
                    this tutorial. This is the most hand holding guide to get you
                    to be able to automatically update your neocities site from a
                    github repository.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrTQipWp6co"
                        >Git and Github 0 Experience to Professional</a
                    > Speaking of not knowing what a git is - this tutorial really
                    helped me understand the basics of what git is and the basics
                    of using it. if you want to get into code or even just using open
                    source programs you should really watch this.
                </li>

                <li>
                    <a
                        href="https://zines.stefanbohacek.com/zines/why-how-website-blog/"
                        >Why and How to Make a Website</a
                    > A quick and easy to read zine about starting a website. Print
                    it out and share it!
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div slot="right-half">
        <h2>so you're <b>not</b> ready?</h2>
        <p>
            very valid. but there are still ways to enjoy the new web and
            personal websites! This section has ways you can participate in
            small web without having to even know what a div is.
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="https://unplatform.fromthesuperhighway.com/"
                    >Unplatform</a
                > An interactive guide (with a fun quiz) to help direct you OFF of
                doomscrolling and social media and towards a better way to intentionally
                use the internet to learn, connect, and enjoy what matters to you.
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://sadgrl.online/guides/surf/"
                    >How to surf the web in the year of our lord 2025</a
                >
            </li>
            <li>
                <a
                    href="https://thoughts.melonking.net/guides/introduction-to-the-web-revival-1-what-is-the-web-revival"
                    >Intro to web revival by melon</a
                >
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://yesterweb.org/"
                    >The yesterweb manifesto for a new web</a
                >
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            <mark>helpful hint</mark> pages titled "links out" or "affiliates" will
            usually lead you to sites recommended by the owner and are a great place
            to discover new pages!
        </p>
        <hr />
        <h3>Useful Tools</h3>
        <p>
            Here are some services that I like that can help with privacy,
            mental wellness, and just making the internet a place to enjoy
            again.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="https://proton.me/mail">Proton Mail</a> encrypted email service
                based in Switzerland, bye gmail
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://brave.com/download/">Brave Browser</a> I dont use
                it all the time but I do like it as a replacement for "incognito mode"
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://filegarden.com/">File Garden</a> Holds files of any
                kind you can link back to later, replace your google drive
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://iamfutureproof.com/">Futureproof</a> A site that
                includes tools, resources, and basic information about online and
                digital safety and it's effects on the human brain.
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://fmhy.net/">fmhy</a> 🏴‍☠️to source all sorts of media.
                there is no ethical consumption under capitalism wooo!
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://everynoise.com/">Every Noise at Once</a> a long-running
                attempt at an algorithmically-generated, readability-adjusted scatter-plot
                of the musical genre-space
            </li>
        </ul>
        <hr />
        <h3>Social Sites</h3>
        <p>
            This isn't social media - the goal of these sites are to connect
            with new faces and find new people.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="https://neocities.org/">Neocities</a> Where this site is
                currently hosted! It's free to host your own site here and a great
                way to find other personal web pages. Even if you don't make a page
                you can create an account to follow your favorite sites.
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://forum.melonland.net/">melonland forum</a> A social
                forum that will send you down a trillion rabbit holes. Good for general
                interests and art.
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://discourse.32bit.cafe/">32 bit cafe</a> A social forum,
                much more modern set up. Good place to talk tech, web, and how the
                internet shapes us
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://www.pi.fyi/">PI FYI</a> Literally just a site for
                recommendations. You can get local recs and share your own
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://pixelfed.org/">pixelfed</a> App, alternative to instagram.
                Basically what if the app never got bought by meta
            </li>
        </ul>
        <img src="/div/heartdiv.png" />
    </div>
</Layout>
